08–1475":"1408–1475","1280–1363":"1280–1363","1429–1463":"1429–1463","–1436":"–1436","–Male":"Deceased","1410–1470":"1410–1470","about 1470":"about 1470","1436":"1436","1435":"1435","BEF    1436":"before 1436","1410":"1410","1475":"1475","1463":"1463","1363":"1363","1470":"1470","1408":"1408","1429":"1429","1280":"1280","Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Scotland, United Kingdom","Kilwinning, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Kilwinning, Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Ayreshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret DeSomerville was born in 1410, in Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Scotland, United Kingdom. She married Sir Knight Duncan KirkPatrick in 1435. They were the parents of at least 4 sons and 2 daughters. She died about 1470, in Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 61."},"et":{"1410–about 1470":"1410–umbes 1470","1408–1475":"1408–1475","1280–1363":"1280–1363","1429–1463":"1429–1463","–1436":"–1436","–Male":"Surnud","1410–1470":"1410–1470","about 1470":"umbes 1470","1436":"1436","1435":"1435","BEF    1436":"enne 1436","1410":"1410","1475":"1475","1463":"1463","1363":"1363","1470":"1470","1408":"1408","1429":"1429","1280":"1280","Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Kilwinning, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Kilwinning, Ayrshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Ayreshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1410–about 1470":"1410–noin 1470","1408–1475":"1408–1475","1280–1363":"1280–1363","1429–1463":"1429–14